# Post-inline-source-fusion baseline (April 2026)
#
# Hardware: WSL2 Ubuntu-24.04 on developer workstation. JDK 21 toolchain. JMH 1.x.
#
# Profile: raw-speed (no Lattice metrics, no logical-edge metrics, parallel GC, AlwaysPreTouch,
# 2g heap) plus the new opt-in inline source-side fusion enabled via
# -Dlattice.fusion.inlineSource=true.
#
# Inline source-side fusion compiles eligible (single-producer, non-preallocated, non-stamped,
# non-handle-typed) sources connected through a fusible BLOCK SPSC edge to a fully-fused
# downstream worker into a "no consumer thread" plan: the producer thread executes the fused
# stage chain synchronously. The consumer worker is still constructed for observability and
# its thread parks until graph stop. Default is OFF; semantics (especially backpressure) of
# inline-fused emit differ from the bounded-queue path, hence the explicit opt-in.
#
# Command:
#   java -Xms2g -Xmx2g -XX:+AlwaysPreTouch -XX:+UseParallelGC \
#     -Dlattice.metrics.hotCounters=false \
#     -Dlattice.metrics.residence=false \
#     -Dlattice.metrics.stageHistograms=false \
#     -Dlattice.runtime.fusedLogicalEdgeMetrics=false \
#     -Dlattice.fusion.inlineSource=true \
#     -jar build/libs/lattice-1.0-SNAPSHOT-jmh.jar \
#     "ApplesToApplesDisruptorBenchmark.(latticeThreeStagePipelineFused|disruptorThreeStagePipelineManuallyFused|latticeThreeStagePipelinePhysical|disruptorThreeStagePipelinePhysical|latticeSpscPreallocated|disruptorSpscPreallocated)" \
#     -wi 3 -i 5 -r 5s -w 5s -f 1 -tu s

